us/1722695167013236744">Arin Dube</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>工资是否恢复到他们的大流行趋势尚不清楚，但是现在它们肯定已经上升了一年，我们已经下降了通货膨胀。</p><p>当然，通货膨胀的下降并不意味着价格恢复到原来的位置。因此，人们可能会习惯新的更高数字需要一段时间，而通货膨胀下降的事实确实陷入了困境。但这就是说，实际上有一些价格已经下跌了，例如汽油价格，现在的价格与十年前的水平大约相同： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/df3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:61592,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fdf3a3fa7-7bbe-4cf5-a9a8-f36a103ae1c5_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>为什么通货膨胀率下降？这两个主要理论是：</p><p> 1）美联储的加息导致通货膨胀率降低，这成为一个自我实现的预言，并且</p><p>2）经济简单地弄清了大流行和乌克兰战争初期的供应方向。</p><p>我们要有一段时间才知道这两个因素有多少贡献，但是我们所知道的是，它们共同起作用。</p><p>认识到这里的“不吠叫”的“狗”也很重要 - 与中国解耦。西方对中国的投资暴跌，但尚无迹象表明这会导致更高的价格。我们对使我们的消费品便宜的“中国价格”的依赖是过去。</p><p>无论如何，低通货膨胀和充分的就业结合在一起，形成了宏观经济野兽最受欢迎的：<strong>消毒的繁荣</strong>。在这种戈德洛克斯的情况下，经济在稳定的价格和出色的就业市场之间并没有面临折衷。鉴于就业市场现在已经<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/LNS12300060">达到了以往的好处</a>，这就是我们现在所处的位置。</p><p>哦，顺便说一句，如果您想知道当前的经济状况是否只是政府支出增加引起的“糖高”：不，这不是发生的事情。如果那是真的，我们现在会看到更多的通货膨胀（就像2021年一样）。 Also, note that government spending as a percentage of GDP has fallen back to about where it was in the 1980s: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:57136,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/png&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F00763745-dfd7-4e4e-bb37-4046b76a95f9_1318x450.png 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> Biden&#39;s industrial policy might be giving the economy a boost, but if so, it&#39;s doing it by “crowding in” private investment, not by spending the money directly.</p><p> Of course, a lot of people are asking: Given these great economic conditions, why are Americans so pessimistic about the economy? And one potential answer is: Just wait, they will be. It probably takes some time and persistent messaging in order for positive economic conditions to make their way into people&#39;s consciousness. For what it&#39;s worth, Biden&#39;s approval rating on the economy seems to be <a href="https://twitter.com/ChrisDJackson/status/1724848223955644616">improving steadily</a> , and consumer sentiment has <a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/UMCSENT">risen quite a bit</a> from its lows a year ago.</p><h4> The 20s tech boom</h4><p> The “Roaring 20s” idea wasn&#39;t just about a strong economy; it was fundamentally about a technology boom. And although it&#39;s hard to identify the impacts of technologies on the economy, I think there are signs that some of the things we were excited about three years ago are now having an effect.</p><p> First, there&#39;s remote work, which I already mentioned. So far, <a href="https://siepr.stanford.edu/publications/working-paper/evolution-working-home">it looks like</a> fully remote work lowers productivity, but allows people to live in cheaper areas, while hybrid work keeps productivity the same while cutting down on commuting costs. This means work-from-home is already cutting costs, and that businesses have improved their ability to use remote work quite a lot from <a href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w31515">the early pandemic days</a> .</p><p> Also, consider MRNA vaccines. Although vaccines for cancer, malaria, and other diseases won&#39;t start having a macroeconomic impact for a while, Covid vaccination probably did. The percentage of Americans age 18-64 receiving Social Security Disability payments was only <a href="https://www.kff.org/medicare/state-indicator/total-disabled-social-security-disability-insurance-ssdi-beneficiaries-ages-18-64/?currentTimeframe=0&amp;sortModel=%7B%22colId%22:%22Location%22,%22sort%22:%22asc%22%7D">3.9% in 2022</a> , compared to <a href="https://www.kff.org/medicare/state-indicator/total-disabled-social-security-disability-insurance-ssdi-beneficiaries-ages-18-64/?currentTimeframe=9&amp;sortModel=%7B%22colId%22:%22Location%22,%22sort%22:%22asc%22%7D">4.8% in 2013</a> . Vaccination reduces the severity of Covid, which likely prevents long-term disability due to lung scarring.</p><p> Then there&#39;s the progress in solar power and batteries. Eventually, this will make electricity a lot cheaper than it was before, allowing businesses to lower costs and liberating them from the notorious wild swings of fossil fuel prices. That will increase productivity. For now, though, solar is only 6% of US electricity generation, so drops in solar costs are, for now, just a percent of a percent — too small to influence overall electricity costs much. And EVs are only 1% of the auto fleet.</p><p> But these technologies are cheap enough to influence business investment. US businesses <a href="https://about.bnef.com/blog/renewable-energy-investment-hits-record-breaking-358-billion-in-1h-2023/">invested $25 billion in solar alone</a> in the first half of 2023. <a href="https://atlaspolicy.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/U.S.-Investments-in-Electric-Vehicle-Manufacturing-2023.pdf">$200 billion</a> of investment in EV manufacturing has been announced in the US so far. That&#39;s helping to support the robust private-sector investment that&#39;s keeping the country at full employment.</p><p> Another technology driving rapid corporate investment is AI. AI is <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-10-17/ai-funding-soars-to-17-9-billion-as-the-rest-of-tech-slumps?sref=R8NfLgwS">rapidly taking over</a> the world of venture finance, with more than a quarter of VC money now<a href="https://news.crunchbase.com/ai-robotics/us-startup-funding-doubled-openai-anthropic-2023/">flowing into the space</a> . That&#39;s partly a result of more traditional startup categories going bust, but mostly it&#39;s about the boom in generative AI following the release of ChatGPT and various AI art apps. <a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/ai-artificial-intelligence-stocks-investing-us-economy-outlook-goldman-sachs-2023-8">Goldman Sachs predicts</a> that AI investment could be 4% of the economy in just two years. Boardroom chaos at OpenAI seems unlikely to slow the trend much, since the basic technology of LLMs is now pretty widely diffused.</p><p> And that&#39;s just <em>today</em> . It&#39;s crucial to note that all of these technologies — new wonder vaccines, solar and batteries, and AI — will almost certainly have a much <em>bigger</em> impact once they&#39;re widely adopted. Generative AI will juice productivity in ways we can&#39;t even imagine right now. Cheap solar and batteries will push down electricity and transportation costs. Using vaccines to<a href="https://www.nih.gov/news-events/nih-research-matters/mrna-vaccine-treat-pancreatic-cancer">treat cancer</a> will reduce disease burden. And further business-model innovations will hopefully allow companies to use work-from-home to greater advantage.</p><p> In other words, the Roaring 20s are just getting started.</p><p> Much of the country is still mired in the atmosphere of pessimism and malaise that followed the Great Recession, the chaotic Trump years, the pandemic, and the post-pandemic inflation. And of course dire events like the Israel-Gaza war continue to dominate headlines. But already I feel like I can sense the green shoots of excitement about the future, from <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/dont-be-a-decel">the online “e/acc” mini-movement</a> to nascent <a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/06/12/economy/new-york-fed-consumer-expectations/index.html">optimism</a> about the economy.</p><p> Now all we have to do is <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-build-nothing-country">quash the NIMBYs</a> , and we&#39;ll be good. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-roaring-20s-are-back-on-track?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-roaring-20s-are-back-on-track?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p>; 
